THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration is planning to change the mix of airplanes and 
helicopters assigned to aircraft carriers, resulting in a Navy-wide loss of one 
full carrier's worth of aircraft, according to a study by the Congressional 
Research Service of the Library of Congress. Rep. George J. Hochbrueckner 
(D-N.Y.), a member of the House Armed Services Committee, requested the study 
as part of efforts by him and Long Island's four other congressmen to save the 
F-14D jet fighter, which was cut from the 1990 budget by Defense Secretary Dick 
Cheney. The F-14D Tomcat is manufactured by Grumman Corp. in Bethpage, N.Y. 
Ronald O'Rourke, the naval analyst who prepared the study, said he learned that 
the Navy is planning to switch in the 1990s from a combination of aircraft 
carrier configurations to a standardized "transitional" air wing, for a 
reduction of 126 to 128 aircraft. 
</P>
