<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Next year's Grammy Awards will include separate categories for hard rock and 
heavy metal acts, the sponsoring National Academy of Recording Arts and 
Sciences has announced. The music awards show came under fire this year when 
the combined hard rock/heavy metal award, in its first year, went to 
progressive rock veteran Jethro Tull over favored metal band Metallica. Other 
changes voted in by the NARAS trustees include limited eligibility for new 
single releases of songs from older albums and the broadening of eligibility 
requirements for the best new artist and producer of the year nominations. 
CLAUDIA PUIG 
